The '''violet-headed hummingbird''' ('''''Klais guimeti''''') is a species of [[hummingbird]] in the family [[Trochilidae]]. It is the only species in the genus '''''Klais'''''.

Its natural [[habitat]]s are [[subtropical or tropical moist lowland forest]], subtropical or tropical moist [[montane forest]], and heavily degraded former [[forest]].

== Taxonomy ==
The violet-headed hummingbird was [[species description|formally described]] in 1843 by the French ornithologist [[Jules Bourcier]] from specimens collected near [[Caracas]] in Venezuela. Bourcier coined the [[binomial name]] ''Trochilus guimeti''.<ref>{{ cite book | editor-last=Peters | editor-first=James Lee | editor-link=James L. Peters | year=1945 | title=Check-List of Birds of the World | volume=5 | publisher=Harvard University Press | place=Cambridge, Massachusetts  | page=29 | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/14480040 }}</ref>  The violet-headed hummingbird is now the only species placed in the genus ''Klais'' that was introduced in 1854 by the German naturalist [[Ludwig Reichenbach]].<ref>{{ cite journal | last=Reichenbach | first=Ludwig | author-link=Ludwig Reichenbach | year=1854 | title=Aufzählung der Colibris Oder Trochilideen in ihrer wahren natürlichen Verwandtschaft, nebst Schlüssel ihrer Synonymik | journal=Journal für Ornithologie (Supplement) | volume=1 | pages=1–24 [13] | language=de | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/13867391 }}</ref><ref name=ioc>{{cite web| editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor1-link=Frank Gill (ornithologist) | editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | editor3-last=Rasmussen | editor3-first=Pamela | editor3-link=Pamela Rasmussen | date=July 2020 | title=Hummingbirds | work=IOC World Bird List Version 10.2 | url=http://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/hummingbirds/ | publisher=International Ornithologists' Union | access-date=5 January 2020 }}</ref> The genus is named after Kleis (or Cleis), the daughter of the Lesbian poet [[Sappho]]. The specific name was chosen to honour the French chemist [[Jean-Baptiste Guimet]].<ref>{{cite book | last=Jobling | first=James A. | year=2010| title=The Helm Dictionary of Scientific Bird Names | publisher=Christopher Helm | location=London | isbn=978-1-4081-2501-4 | pages=181, 214–215 }}</ref>

Three [[subspecies]] are recognised:<ref name=ioc/>
* ''K. g. merrittii'' ([[George Newbold Lawrence|Lawrence]], 1860) – east Honduras to east Panama
* ''K. g. guimeti'' ([[Jules Bourcier|Bourcier]], 1843) – east Colombia and north Venezuela to east Ecuador and extreme north Peru
* ''K. g. pallidiventris'' [[Jan Sztolcman|Stolzmann]], 1926 – east Peru and west Bolivia

== Description ==
Violet-headed hummingbirds are on average {{convert|8.1|cm|in|abbr=on}} in length with a short, straight [[beak|bill]] that averages {{convert|13|mm|in|abbr=on}} in length.{{sfn|Hilty|Brown|1986|p=262}} The head and throat of the male are intense violet or blue (depending on the angle viewed) with white spots behind each eye that stands out against the dark head. The back is metallic bluish-green (or bronze-green depending on the angle) and breast is green fading to a grey belly. The tail is green with tiny white-grey tail spots. The wings are black.{{sfn|Hilty|Brown|1986|p=262}}{{sfn|Dunning|Ridgely|1982|p=225}}{{sfn|Skutch|1958|p=5}}{{sfn|de Schauensee|Phelps|1978|p=139}}

The female is duller with a blue cap, green back and grey throat, breast and belly. The wings and tail are the same as the male. The female also has the white spot behind the eye.{{sfn|Hilty|Brown|1986|p=262}}{{sfn|Dunning|Ridgely|1982|p=225}}{{sfn|Skutch|1958|p=5}}{{sfn|de Schauensee|Phelps|1978|p=139}}

== Distribution and habitat==
The violet-headed hummingbird ranges from [[Central America]] well into [[South America]]. This includes Honduras, Nicaragua, Costa Rica and Panama in Central America and western Venezuela, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, northern Brazil, western Venezuela and northern Bolivia.{{sfn|Hilty|Brown|1986|p=262}}{{sfn|Dunning|Ridgely|1982|p=225}}{{sfn|Skutch|1958|p=5}}{{sfn|de Schauensee|Phelps|1978|p=139}} The species tends to be local in distribution, common in some areas and rare in other seemingly identical areas.{{sfn|Hilty|Brown|1986|p=262}}<ref name=Jones/>

The violet-headed hummingbird occurs in the mountains and has been recorded to occur from {{convert|200|to|850|m|ft|abbr=on}} in Costa Rica,{{sfn|Skutch|1958|p=5}} from {{convert|400|to|1850|m|ft|abbr=on}} in Colombia{{sfn|Hilty|Brown|1986|p=262}} and {{convert|150|to|1900|m|ft|abbr=on}} in Venezuela.{{sfn|de Schauensee|Phelps|1978|p=139}}

Violet-headed hummingbirds are found on the edges of humid [[primary forest]], openings in [[secondary forest]]s, in shrub and thicket clearings{{sfn|Hilty|Brown|1986|p=262}}{{sfn|Dunning|Ridgely|1982|p=225}} and in various human modified habitat such as ''[[Stachytarpheta]]'' hedges in Costa Rica{{sfn|Skutch|1958|p=6}} and [[shade-grown coffee]] plantations in Venezuela.<ref name=Jones/>

==Behaviour==
=== Breeding ===
In Costa Rica, males sing in loose [[Lek (mating arena)|leks]]{{sfn|Hilty|Brown|1986|p=262}} beginning in October and intensifying until the breeding season in December.{{sfn|Skutch|1958|p=9}} The chorus continues until the dry season causes the flowers to disappear in February and March. The chorus picks up again when the rains begin again in April, but the heavy rains of May shut the chorus down again until October.{{sfn|Skutch|1958|p=9}} The leks are located {{convert|5|to|18|m|ft|abbr=on}} above the ground on the edge of clearings where the males sing conspicuously from slender dead twigs.{{sfn|Skutch|1958|pp=9-10}} Occasionally, an individual will sing solo without other violet-headed hummingbirds nearby.{{sfn|Hilty|Brown|1986|p=262}}

The [[Bird nest#Cup|nest]] is a mossy cup{{sfn|Hilty|Brown|1986|p=262}} built {{convert|1|to|5|m|ft|abbr=on}} above forested mountain streams. They are normally built in February,{{sfn|Skutch|1958|p=11}} but sometimes as early as January.{{sfn|Hilty|Brown|1986|p=262}} The last young [[fledge]] in May.{{sfn|Hilty|Brown|1986|p=262}}{{sfn|Skutch|1958|p=11}}

=== Food and feeding===
The violet-headed hummingbird drinks [[nectar]] from understory flowering shrubs as well as taking small [[insect]]s<ref name=Jones/> on the wing.{{sfn|Hilty|Brown|1986|p=262}} In Costa Rica, a particular fondness for ''[[Stachytarpheta]]'' flowers has been reported with as many as one individual every {{convert|5|–|7|m|ft|abbr=on}} on a hedge near Murcia.{{sfn|Skutch|1958|p=6}}

== Relationship with humans ==
The violet-headed hummingbird has been designated as a species of [[Least Concern]] due to its large range and ability to exist in human modified habitat.<ref name="iucn status 13 November 2021" /><ref name=Jones/> The flowering shrubs near Murcia, Costa Rica, were reported to be in an area cleared for [[agriculture]] with very few trees.{{sfn|Skutch|1958|p=6}}

